**Blue Nile tennis bracelets are worth buying — but only if you understand the lab vs natural math first.** A 3ct lab-grown four-prong is $2,485. The same design in natural diamond is $5,870. Same look on your wrist. Same 14K gold. The difference is $3,385 and a resale market that doesn't exist for lab stones. I'll help you decide which one makes sense for you.

I've gone through every Blue Nile tennis bracelet in the current catalog for {{month_year}}: four-prong round, bezel set, floating, emerald cut, oval, princess cut, and the James Allen designs that migrated over after that brand shutdown. Real prices. Real per-carat math. Affiliate disclosure: Blue Nile pays a commission if you buy through my links. It doesn't change what I write.

