## The Lab vs Natural Question: What Actually Matters

This is what most people are really searching for, so I'll answer it directly before anything else.

**Lab-grown diamonds are physically identical to mined diamonds.** Same hardness. Same sparkle. Same crystal structure. A gemologist cannot tell the difference with the naked eye — only specialized equipment can. So if you're asking "will it look real?" — yes, completely.

**The difference is price and resale.** Here's the actual math from Blue Nile's current catalog:

| Style | Lab-Grown | Natural | Price Gap |
|---|---|---|---|
| 4-Prong Round 3ct | $2,485 | $5,870 | $3,385 |
| Two-Prong Round 5ct | $3,374 | ~$10,000+ | ~$6,600+ |
| Emerald Cut 5ct | $5,710 | $8,029 | $2,319 |
| Emerald Cut 10ct | $10,500 | $16,184 | $5,684 |

[![Blue Nile Emerald Cut Lab-Grown Diamond Tennis Bracelet in 14K Yellow Gold 12ct — step-cut stones in yellow gold](/images/blue-nile-emerald-cut-tennis-bracelet-yellow-gold-12ct.avif)](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/7-emerald-cut-lab-grown-diamond-tennis-bracelet-in-14k-yellow-gold-12-ct-tw-f-g-vs2-si1-item-252265?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blue_nile_reviews)

**Who should buy lab-grown:** You want maximum diamond size for the budget. You don't plan to resell it. You just want it to look beautiful every day — and it will.

**Who should buy natural:** You're buying as a significant gift or milestone piece. You want the item to hold some value over time. Natural diamond prices have historically held; lab diamond resale value has collapsed as production costs dropped.

The honest answer? **For a tennis bracelet you plan to wear daily and love — lab is the smart choice.** For a 10th anniversary gift meant to last a lifetime — natural diamond is worth the premium.

