## Wrist Sizing: The Problem Nobody Mentions Until It's Too Late

**Standard Blue Nile tennis bracelets are 7 inches.** That's the industry standard, and it fits most women's wrists comfortably — enough to move without sliding off, not so tight it digs in.

**How to measure:** Wrap a flexible tape measure or piece of string around your wrist just below the wrist bone. Add 0.5" to 1" for comfort. Most women measure 6"–7" at the wrist, which puts the 7" bracelet right.

| Wrist Measurement | Recommended Bracelet |
|---|---|
| Under 6" | Consider a 6.5" (Blue Nile doesn't stock this — ask about resizing) |
| 6"–6.5" | 7" standard — snug but comfortable |
| 6.5"–7" | 7" standard — ideal fit |
| Over 7" | 7" will fit but may feel tight — check if sizing is available |

**Practical note:** Blue Nile lists all tennis bracelets as 7". If you need a different length, you'd need to have a local jeweler add or remove links after purchase. This is a normal alteration, not a defect. A jeweler typically charges $30–$80 to resize a tennis bracelet.

**For gifts:** 7" is the right guess for most adult women. If in doubt, go 7" and plan for a possible minor alteration.

