## Setting Styles: 4-Prong vs Bezel vs Floating vs Two-Prong

The setting style changes the look, the security, and the price. Here's what each means:

**Four-prong (classic):** Each diamond is held by four tiny gold prongs. This is the traditional tennis bracelet look — maximum light, classic sparkle, the style that's been on wrists since Chris Evert made them famous in 1987. Four prongs hold stones well, but they're also the most snag-prone on sweaters and fine fabrics.

**Bezel set:** Each diamond is fully encircled by a thin rim of metal. The most secure setting — stones cannot fall out. Looks more modern and minimal. Slightly less sparkle because the metal covers more of the diamond's edge. Best for active wear, frequent gym-goers, or people who work with their hands.

**Floating / shared prong:** Adjacent stones share prongs between them, so there's almost no visible metal. Maximum sparkle. The most delicate setting — more risk of snagging over time. Best for special occasions, not daily wear in rough environments.

**Two-prong:** Minimalist setting with just two prongs per stone. Very sleek look, more diamond visible. Less stone security than four-prong for the same reason — fewer prongs means each prong carries more load.

**East-West bezel:** Stones are set horizontally (long axis runs along the length of the bracelet) rather than face-up. Very contemporary look. Only available in emerald and marquise cuts at Blue Nile.

[![Blue Nile East-West Bezel Marquise Diamond Tennis Bracelet in Platinum — architectural E/W bezel setting](/images/blue-nile-marquise-tennis-bracelet-white-gold.avif)](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/bracelets/east-west-bezel-tennis-bracelet-with-5-ctw-marquise-cut-diamonds-in-platinum-item-297347?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blue_nile_reviews)

**My recommendation:** For daily wear, bezel or four-prong. For special occasions or gifts, floating or four-prong. For a fashion-forward look, E/W bezel with emerald cuts.

