## FAQ: Blue Nile Tennis Bracelets

**Is the 7" standard tennis bracelet too long or too short?**
It fits most adult women's wrists. Measure your wrist and add 0.5–1" — if that number is close to 7", you're fine. If your wrist is unusually small (under 5.5") or large (over 7"), plan for a local jeweler adjustment after purchase.

**Does a Blue Nile tennis bracelet come in a gift box?**
Yes. Blue Nile ships all jewelry in branded packaging — a blue box with ribbon, inside a Blue Nile outer shipping box. Gift-ready as shipped. If you need gift wrapping beyond the box, they offer that at checkout for a small fee.

**Can I return it if it doesn't fit?**
Yes. Blue Nile's 30-day return policy covers tennis bracelets. Return shipping is free. The bracelet must be unworn and in original condition. If you've had a jeweler resize it, return is no longer straightforward — size first only if you're sure.

**What's the difference between lab-grown and natural for tennis bracelets specifically?**
Visually: nothing. Both are real diamonds. The price difference is significant (often 50–70% cheaper for lab). The resale difference is significant in the other direction — lab diamond resale values have dropped substantially. For a bracelet you plan to wear and keep, lab is smart. For a bracelet you might eventually sell or pass down, natural holds value better.

**Do Blue Nile tennis bracelets use real gold?**
Yes. All 14K and 18K pieces are stamped with the correct hallmarks. 14K white gold contains 58.3% pure gold. Platinum pieces are stamped PT950.

**Will H-I color diamonds look yellow in a tennis bracelet?**
At bracelet distance — no. H-I is near-colorless. You'll see warmth only when comparing directly against a D-F stone under magnification. In daily wear, H-I stones in a tennis bracelet read white. In white gold or platinum, this is especially true.

**Is the box clasp safe enough?**
For normal daily wear, yes. If you're very active or have anxiety about security, visit a local jeweler after purchase and ask them to add a figure-8 safety clasp for $30–$50. This is standard practice for high-value tennis bracelets.

**Can I stack Blue Nile tennis bracelets?**
Yes. The 7" length works with standard stacking. The four-prong and bezel designs stack especially well because they sit flat without excessive height. The floating/shared-prong design has a slightly higher profile and can catch on adjacent bracelets, so test before committing to daily stacking.

**What about the James Allen tennis bracelets now on Blue Nile?**
The Flower Clasp tennis bracelet exists in both lab-grown ($2,015) and natural diamond ($3,445) versions. Both have the flower clasp detail, which is more decorative than the standard Blue Nile box clasp. JA.com is shutting down and inventory is being cleared, but these particular designs appear to be staying in the Blue Nile catalog as part of the James Allen collection integration.

**How long does shipping take?**
Standard shipping takes 5–7 business days. Expedited options are available. Free shipping on orders over $500 (which covers all tennis bracelets on this page).

**Is free engraving available on tennis bracelets?**
Tennis bracelets are not typically engraved — the links are too small for standard engraving. Blue Nile doesn't offer engraving on their tennis bracelet styles. If personalization matters, a custom charm or pendant layered with the bracelet is a better option.

**Can Blue Nile resize the bracelet after purchase?**
Blue Nile doesn't offer in-house resizing. A local jeweler can add or remove links for $30–$80. This is standard practice and doesn't void any warranty.

**Which setting style is best for someone who is very active?**
Bezel — full bezel setting encircles each stone completely. No prong to snag, no prong to bend. The E/W bezel emerald cut and the platinum bezel natural diamond bracelet are the two most secure options in the catalog.

**What's the best Blue Nile tennis bracelet as a gift?**
The natural 3ct four-prong in 14K white gold at $5,870 — 390 reviews, the classic look, real diamonds. If budget is tighter, the lab-grown 3ct four-prong at $2,485 (30% off) is the thoughtful under-$3K option. For something distinctive: the E/W bezel emerald cut lab at $6,210.

